'2022-04-20T16:00:04Z', 'author_association': 'CONTRIBUTOR', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'Now that OpenSSL supports a sufficiently high quality RNG, we can remove our internal implementation of AES-CTR-DRBG and just use theirs. This reduces the amount of code we need to maintain and also opens up a path to supporting `SecureRandom` on `aarch64`  (see #40) as we will depend on OpenSSL for proper (re)seeding as well. (Our manual seeding solution is X86_64 only.)

Links for reference:
* https://www.openssl.org/docs/man1.1.1/man3/RAND_DRBG_new.html
* https://www.openssl.org/docs/man1.1.1/man3/RAND_DRBG_generate.html
* https://www.openssl.org/docs/man1.1.1/man3/RAND_DRBG_get0_private.html (`RAND_DRBG_get0_private` after properly configuring the default in [our library initialization](https://github.com/corretto/amazon-corretto-crypto-provider/blob/develop/csrc/loader.cpp#L28) may be completely sufficient. This strategy may also address #121 by removing some `ThreadLocal` state.)
* https://www.openssl.org/docs/man1.1.1/man3/RAND_DRBG_set_reseed_defaults.html (Both for defaults and to implement `SecureRandom.setSeed()` ([Default values appear to be every 256 calls and hour](https://github.com/openssl/openssl/blob/15f54941bd4c0324f1c8d7773db56004183a9cb7/providers/implementations/rands/drbg_local.h#L30-L31). This is likely fine for our use and will result in us not needing to override it. Number of calls is definitely fine. I might lower the time interval to a small number of minutes.)

This change adds a new SecureRandom implementation to ACCP that internally just calls AWS-LC's `RAND_bytes()` API. This RNG is seeded from an internal CPU jitter implementation on first use, and mixes in entropy from RDRAND on x86 platforms when available, or from system OS entropy when not.

 resolves #2989
### Description of changes: 

gcc-11 added a new error called array-parameter, which warns about redeclarations of functions involving arguments of array or pointer types of inconsistent kinds ([See release notes for more details](https://gcc.gnu.org/gcc-11/changes.html)). I fixed the places where these inconsistencies occur, in most cases, I just changed the function declaration to match the definition.
### Call-outs:

I did not add gcc11 to our build, that might be a future project, although it should be pretty easy.
### Testing:

s2n can be compiled with gcc11 with -Werror turned on. Basically I just did 'make CC=gcc-11'

 Is this a refactor change? If so, how have you proved that the intended behavior hasn't changed?

Prerequisite work needed for https://github.com/corretto/amazon-corretto-crypto-provider/issues/139

*Description of changes:*
This change adds a new SecureRandom implementation to ACCP that internally just calls AWS-LC's `RAND_bytes()` API. This RNG is seeded from an internal CPU jitter implementation on first use, and mixes in entropy from RDRAND on x86 platforms when available, or from system OS entropy when not. 

Once this new SecureRandom implementation is approved and integrated, we can proceed with removing the AesCtrDrbg as described in the linked issue and migrate uses over to this implementation.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that you can use, modify, copy, and redistribute this contribution, under the terms of your choice.

Prerequisite work needed for https://github.com/corretto/amazon-corretto-crypto-provider/issues/139

*Description of changes:*
This change adds a new SecureRandom implementation to ACCP that internally just calls AWS-LC's `RAND_bytes()` API. This RNG is seeded from an internal CPU jitter implementation on first use, and mixes in entropy from RDRAND on x86 platforms when available, or from system OS entropy when not. 

Once this new SecureRandom implementation is approved and integrated, we can proceed with removing the AesCtrDrbg as described in the linked issue and migrate uses over to this implementation.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that you can use, modify, copy, and redistribute this contribution, under the terms of your choice.

warning:
```console
/usr/bin/ld.gold: warning: aws-s2n/_objs/pq-crypto-sike/sikep434r3_fp_x64_asm.pic.o: \
                           missing .note.GNU-stack section implies executable stack
```

### Resolved issues:

 Linker error.

### Description of changes: 

On Linux/GNU, explicitly provide a `.note.GNU-stack` section for the file.

### Call-outs:

It is better to fix this in the source file than using `-Wa,--noexecstack`.

### Testing:

Tested on GNU/Linux to address the above described linker error. Does not affect functionality.

When using the GNU linker, it produces the following
warning:
```console
/usr/bin/ld.gold: warning: aws-s2n/_objs/pq-crypto-sike/sikep434r3_fp_x64_asm.pic.o: \
                           missing .note.GNU-stack section implies executable stack
```

### Resolved issues:

 Linker error.

### Description of changes: 

On Linux/GNU, explicitly provide a `.note.GNU-stack` section for the file.

### Call-outs:

It is better to fix this in the source file than using `-Wa,--noexecstack`.

### Testing:

Tested on GNU/Linux to address the above described linker error. Does not affect functionality.

When using the GNU linker, it produces the following
warning:
```console
/usr/bin/ld.gold: warning: aws-s2n/_objs/pq-crypto-sike/sikep434r3_fp_x64_asm.pic.o: \
                           missing .note.GNU-stack section implies executable stack
```

### Resolved issues:

 Linker error.

### Description of changes: 

On Linux/GNU, explicitly provide a `.note.GNU-stack` section for the file.

### Call-outs:

It is better to fix this in the source file than using `-Wa,--noexecstack`.

### Testing:

Tested on GNU/Linux to address the above described linker error. Does not affect functionality.

Prerequisite work needed for https://github.com/corretto/amazon-corretto-crypto-provider/issues/139

*Description of changes:*
This change adds a new SecureRandom implementation to ACCP that internally just calls AWS-LC's `RAND_bytes()` API. This RNG is seeded from an internal CPU jitter implementation on first use, and mixes in entropy from RDRAND on x86 platforms when available, or from system OS entropy when not. 

Once this new SecureRandom implementation is approved and integrated, we can proceed with removing the AesCtrDrbg as described in the linked issue and migrate uses over to this implementation.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that you can use, modify, copy, and redistribute this contribution, under the terms of your choice.

Prerequisite work needed for https://github.com/corretto/amazon-corretto-crypto-provider/issues/139

*Description of changes:*
This change adds a new SecureRandom implementation to ACCP that internally just calls AWS-LC's `RAND_bytes()` API. This RNG is seeded from an internal CPU jitter implementation on first use, and mixes in entropy from RDRAND on x86 platforms when available, or from system OS entropy when not. 

Once this new SecureRandom implementation is approved and integrated, we can proceed with removing the AesCtrDrbg as described in the linked issue and migrate uses over to this implementation.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that you can use, modify, copy, and redistribute this contribution, under the terms of your choice.

Prerequisite work needed for https://github.com/corretto/amazon-corretto-crypto-provider/issues/139

*Description of changes:*
This change adds a new SecureRandom implementation to ACCP that internally just calls AWS-LC's `RAND_bytes()` API. This RNG is seeded from an internal CPU jitter implementation on first use, and mixes in entropy from RDRAND on x86 platforms when available, or from system OS entropy when not. 

Once this new SecureRandom implementation is approved and integrated, we can proceed with removing the AesCtrDrbg as described in the linked issue and migrate uses over to this implementation.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that you can use, modify, copy, and redistribute this contribution, under the terms of your choice.

Prerequisite work needed for https://github.com/corretto/amazon-corretto-crypto-provider/issues/139

*Description of changes:*
This change adds a new SecureRandom implementation to ACCP that internally just calls AWS-LC's `RAND_bytes()` API. This RNG is seeded from an internal CPU jitter implementation on first use, and mixes in entropy from RDRAND on x86 platforms when available, or from system OS entropy when not. 

Once this new SecureRandom implementation is approved and integrated, we can proceed with removing the AesCtrDrbg as described in the linked issue and migrate uses over to this implementation.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that you can use, modify, copy, and redistribute this contribution, under the terms of your choice.

Prerequisite work needed for https://github.com/corretto/amazon-corretto-crypto-provider/issues/139

*Description of changes:*
This change adds a new SecureRandom implementation to ACCP that internally just calls AWS-LC's `RAND_bytes()` API. This RNG is seeded from an internal CPU jitter implementation on first use, and mixes in entropy from RDRAND on x86 platforms when available, or from system OS entropy when not. 

Once this new SecureRandom implementation is approved and integrated, we can proceed with removing the AesCtrDrbg as described in the linked issue and migrate uses over to this implementation.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that you can use, modify, copy, and redistribute this contribution, under the terms of your choice.

N/A


### Description of changes: 
Removes the PQ Hybrid Known Answer Test as it depends on internal Openssl DRBG calling patterns to never change, and breaks the s2n build with newer versions of Openssl. 

`s2n_pq_kem_hybrid_kat_test.c` is brittle to changes to how Openssl calls it's DRBG. This test seeds Openssl's internal DRBG with an all zero value, disables DRBG prediction resistance, then generates brand new client and server PQ and ECDHE key shares using the DRBG, performs a hybrid key exchange with those values, and then asserts that the key exchange values sent over the wire match what the KAT file says they should be. 

Any internal change to Openssl DRBG calling patterns will desynchronize the DRBG from it's expected state, resulting in different key shares to be generated, and causing the KAT test to fail. This means that the s2n build will break on perfectly acceptable changes to Openssl's internal calling patterns to it's DRBG, and make s2n incompatible with newer versions of Openssl.

### Call-outs:
We have [other PQ Known Answer Tests](https://github.com/aws/s2n-tls/pull/3226) that do not depend on knowing the internal DRBG state of Openssl, so we still have test coverage of all PQ KEM's. 

### Testing:

**How is this change tested (unit tests, fuzz tests, etc.)? Are there any testing steps to be verified by the reviewer?**
Tested locally

**Is this a refactor change? If so, how have you proved that the intended behavior hasn't changed?**
No

N/A


### Description of changes: 
Removes the PQ Hybrid Known Answer Test as it depends on internal Openssl DRBG calling patterns to never change, and breaks the s2n build with newer versions of Openssl. 

`s2n_pq_kem_hybrid_kat_test.c` is brittle to changes to how Openssl calls it's DRBG. This test seeds Openssl's internal DRBG with an all zero value, disables DRBG prediction resistance, then generates brand new client and server PQ and ECDHE key shares using the DRBG, performs a hybrid key exchange with those values, and then asserts that the key exchange values sent over the wire match what the KAT file says they should be. 

Any internal change to Openssl DRBG calling patterns will desynchronize the DRBG from it's expected state, resulting in different key shares to be generated, and failing the KAT test. This means that the s2n build will break on perfectly acceptable changes to Openssl's internal calling patterns to it's DRBG, and make s2n incompatible with newer versions of Openssl.

### Call-outs:
We have [other PQ Known Answer Tests](https://github.com/aws/s2n-tls/pull/3226) that do not depend on knowing the internal DRBG state of Openssl, so we still have test coverage of all PQ KEM's. 

### Testing:

**How is this change tested (unit tests, fuzz tests, etc.)? Are there any testing steps to be verified by the reviewer?**
Tested locally

**Is this a refactor change? If so, how have you proved that the intended behavior hasn't changed?**
No

Prerequisite work needed for https://github.com/corretto/amazon-corretto-crypto-provider/issues/139

*Description of changes:*
This change adds a new SecureRandom implementation to ACCP that internally just calls AWS-LC's `RAND_bytes()` API. This RNG is seeded from an internal CPU jitter implementation on first use, and mixes in entropy from RDRAND on x86 platforms when available, or from system OS entropy when not. 

Once this new SecureRandom implementation is approved and integrated, we can proceed with removing the AesCtrDrbg as described in the linked issue and migrate uses over to this implementation.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that you can use, modify, copy, and redistribute this contribution, under the terms of your choice.

*Description of changes:*
This change adds a new SecureRandom implementation to ACCP that internally just calls AWS-LC's `RAND_bytes()` API. This RNG is seeded from an internal CPU jitter implementation on first use, and mixes in entropy from RDRAND on x86 platforms when available, or from system OS entropy when not. 

Once this new SecureRandom implementation is approved and integrated, we can proceed with removing the AesCtrDrbg as described in the linked issue and migrate uses over to this implementation.

Prerequisite work needed for https://github.com/corretto/amazon-corretto-crypto-provider/issues/139

*Description of changes:*
This change adds a new SecureRandom implementation to ACCP that internally just calls AWS-LC's `RAND_bytes()` API. This RNG is seeded from an internal CPU jitter implementation on first use, and mixes in entropy from RDRAND on x86 platforms when available, or from system OS entropy when not. 

Once this new SecureRandom implementation is approved and integrated, we can proceed with removing the AesCtrDrbg as described in the linked issue and migrate uses over to this implementation.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that you can use, modify, copy, and redistribute this contribution, under the terms of your choice.

Prerequisite work needed for https://github.com/corretto/amazon-corretto-crypto-provider/issues/139

*Description of changes:*
This change adds a new SecureRandom implementation to ACCP that internally just calls AWS-LC's `RAND_bytes()` API. This RNG is seeded from an internal CPU jitter implementation on first use, and mixes in entropy from RDRAND on x86 platforms when available, or from system OS entropy when not. 

Once this new SecureRandom implementation is approved and integrated, we can proceed with removing the AesCtrDrbg as described in the linked issue and migrate uses over to this implementation.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that you can use, modify, copy, and redistribute this contribution, under the terms of your choice.

Prerequisite work needed for https://github.com/corretto/amazon-corretto-crypto-provider/issues/139

*Description of changes:*
This change adds a new SecureRandom implementation to ACCP that internally just calls AWS-LC's `RAND_bytes()` API. This RNG is seeded from an internal CPU jitter implementation on first use, and mixes in entropy from RDRAND on x86 platforms when available, or from system OS entropy when not. 

Once this new SecureRandom implementation is approved and integrated, we can proceed with removing the AesCtrDrbg as described in the linked issue and migrate uses over to this implementation.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that you can use, modify, copy, and redistribute this contribution, under the terms of your choice.

*Description of changes:*
This change adds a new SecureRandom implementation to ACCP that internally just calls AWS-LC's `RAND_bytes()` API. This RNG is seeded from an internal CPU jitter implementation on first use, and mixes in entropy from RDRAND on x86 platforms when available, or from system OS entropy when not. 

Once this new SecureRandom implementation is approved and integrated, we can proceed with removing the AesCtrDrbg as described in the linked issue and migrate uses over to this implementation.

Prerequisite work needed for https://github.com/corretto/amazon-corretto-crypto-provider/issues/139

*Description of changes:*
This change adds a new SecureRandom implementation to ACCP that internally just calls AWS-LC's `RAND_bytes()` API. This RNG is seeded from an internal CPU jitter implementation on first use, and mixes in entropy from RDRAND on x86 platforms when available, or from system OS entropy when not. 

Once this new SecureRandom implementation is approved and integrated, we can proceed with removing the AesCtrDrbg as described in the linked issue and migrate uses over to this implementation.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that you can use, modify, copy, and redistribute this contribution, under the terms of your choice.

Prerequisite work needed for https://github.com/corretto/amazon-corretto-crypto-provider/issues/139

*Description of changes:*
This change adds a new SecureRandom implementation to ACCP that internally just calls AWS-LC's `RAND_bytes()` API. This RNG is seeded from an internal CPU jitter implementation on first use, and mixes in entropy from RDRAND on x86 platforms when available, or from system OS entropy when not. 

Once this new SecureRandom implementation is approved and integrated, we can proceed with removing the AesCtrDrbg as described in the linked issue and migrate uses over to this implementation.

Prerequisite work needed for https://github.com/corretto/amazon-corretto-crypto-provider/issues/139

*Description of changes:*
This change adds a new SecureRandom implementation to ACCP that internally just calls AWS-LC's `RAND_bytes()` API. This RNG is seeded from an internal CPU jitter implementation on first use, and mixes in entropy from RDRAND on x86 platforms when available, or from system OS entropy when not. 

Once this new SecureRandom implementation is approved and integrated, we can proceed with removing the AesCtrDrbg as described in the linked issue and migrate uses over to this implementation.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that you can use, modify, copy, and redistribute this contribution, under the terms of your choice.

Prerequisite work needed for https://github.com/corretto/amazon-corretto-crypto-provider/issues/139

*Description of changes:*
This change adds a new SecureRandom implementation to ACCP that internally just calls AWS-LC's `RAND_bytes()` API. This RNG is seeded from an internal CPU jitter implementation on first use, and mixes in entropy from RDRAND on x86 platforms when available, or from system OS entropy when not. 

Once this new SecureRandom implementation is approved and integrated, we can proceed with removing the AesCtrDrbg as described in the linked issue and migrate uses over to this implementation.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that you can use, modify, copy, and redistribute this contribution, under the terms of your choice.

Prerequisite work needed for https://github.com/corretto/amazon-corretto-crypto-provider/issues/139

*Description of changes:*
This change adds a new SecureRandom implementation to ACCP that internally just calls AWS-LC's `RAND_bytes()` API. This RNG is seeded from an internal CPU jitter implementation on first use, and mixes in entropy from RDRAND on x86 platforms when available, or from system OS entropy when not. 

Once this new SecureRandom implementation is approved and integrated, we can proceed with removing the AesCtrDrbg as described in the linked issue and migrate uses over to this implementation.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that you can use, modify, copy, and redistribute this contribution, under the terms of your choice.

First step needed for https://github.com/corretto/amazon-corretto-crypto-provider/issues/139

*Description of changes:*
This change adds a new SecureRandom implementation to ACCP that internally just calls AWS-LC's `RAND_bytes()` API. This RNG is seeded from an internal CPU jitter implementation on first use, and mixes in entropy from RDRAND on x86 platforms when available, or from system OS entropy when not. 

Once this new SecureRandom implementation is approved and integrated, we can proceed with removing the AesCtrDrbg as described in the linked issue and migrate uses over to this implementation.

By submitting this pull request, I confirm that you can use, modify, copy, and redistribute this contribution, under the terms of your choice.

s2n-bignum original commit: https://github.com/awslabs/s2n-bignum/commit/e135d896544a0d63b7bed74675216d7f36d76aa8', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/alexw91/aws-lc/commits/8917b847938216a1b410b2482f69b67ba707ca2e'}, {'sha': '6e366dc0377f3a51e9a526bc83dd8e2183a857f0', 'author': {'email': 'jargh@amazon.com', 'name': 'John Harrison'}, 'message': 'Add 256-bit and 384-bit big-endian conversions

The functions are called "bignum_bigendian_4" (4 words = 256 bits) and
"bignum_bigendian_6" (6 words = 384 bits), with additional aliases
using names "...frombytes..." and "...tobytes...", treating either
input or output as a byte array (exactly the same code, but with a
different type in the C prototype). Each such alias has its own
variant correctness theorem stated slightly differently.

Although they are not specific to the P-256 and P-384 primes (only
their native sizes) they are located in the respective "p256" and
"p384" subdirectories, since the main anticipated uses are in
connection with those primes.

For a little-endian platform, these always amount to byte reversal.
The ARM code has not been tested in a big-endian instantiation, and
since the current ARM model assumes little-endianness a priori,
neither has it been verified in a big-endian setting, but it is
supposed to work there. This is not relevant for x86, which is always
little-endian.

are only specific to the native sizes not the specific primes.

s2n-bignum original commit: https://github.com/awslabs/s2n-bignum/commit/355736c621d486117a0e585776d91816ff724ce1', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/alexw91/aws-lc/commits/2c9862d786fa357ee8c277cbfaefb9a5a1680084'}, {'sha': '53f5c4bcffc23f158f5a29432f21c31248f89d95', 'author': {'email': 'jargh@amazon.com', 'name': 'John Harrison'}, 'message': 'Remove separate almost-Montgomery functions for P-256 and P-384

The almost-Montgomery multiplications and squarings, where full
modular reduction is not guaranteed, do not seem to offer enough
(or in many cases any) performance advantage at the small sizes
of P-256 and P-384, in contrast to larger RSA-sized operations.
These separate functions have been completely deleted, but the
proofs of the "full" Montgomery operations for the NIST primes
(bignum_montmul_p256 etc.) have been augmented with variants
showing that they also work as almost-Montgomery functions. That
is, even without assumptions on the input ranges beyond those
implicit in the native sizes, the appropriate congruence is
guaranteed. It would perhaps be more elegant to put both of these
statements in the same proof, since the current change involves
some duplication of the proof scripts.

s2n-bignum original commit: https://github.com/awslabs/s2n-bignum/commit/6bb45d87e9cd6822e1b926499c718296e8e2a2df', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/alexw91/aws-lc/commits/53f5c4bcffc23f158f5a29432f21c31248f89d95'}, {'sha': '94597746d1d6e161e8f6fe521c32c1cfd46f22d0', 'author': {'email': 'jargh@amazon.com', 'name': 'John Harrison'}, 'message': 'Add first P-521 function, modular addition

This starts a new section "p521" devoted to special optimizations
related to the NIST P-521 curve, where the underlying field has
characteristic 2^521 - 1, a Mersenne prime. The function
bignum_add_p521 is modular addition w.r.t. this prime, by analogy with
the existing bignum_add_p256 and bignum_add_p384 functions.

The code previously had a mix of cases where the "#" prefix was
used before numeric literals and cases where it wasn't. It makes
no difference to gcc or the GNU assembler (and hence this change
does not alter the object files or the proofs) but this makes
things more consistent and may help other tools processing the
ARM asm files.

This makes sure each .S file has an explicit .text directive, and
also regularizes the positioning of these and the .globl ones (plus
the .intel_syntax ones for x86), collecting them at the beginning
just after the initial API comment banner. The only even slightly
non-trivial change is the removal of the global directive for
bignum_of_word_nontrivial in "x86/generic/bignum_of_word.S"
(this was not present for ARM, nor was it declared in the header).
There are no changes to code and hence no changes in the proofs.

s2n-bignum original commit: https://github.com/awslabs/s2n-bignum/commit/debfd4cbdd1db43c1df861dc185d07551b2503eb', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/alexw91/aws-lc/commits/e8f61ab56f0b12c9153d47472b179c291294ff19'}, {'sha': '11f9fbb3008e3507561991f82a7226555bec99e2', 'author': {'email': 'jargh@amazon.com', 'name': 'John Harrison'}, 'message': 'Add non-executable stack directives to all asm files

This appends the following additional directive at the end of each
assembler file, so that the .o produced doesn't appear to need
executable stack:

  #if defined(__linux__) && defined(__ELF__)
  .section .note.GNU-stack,"",%progbits
  #endif

This follows the guidance here:

  https://wiki.gentoo.org/wiki/Hardened/GNU_stack_quickstart#Patching

s2n-bignum original commit: https://github.com/awslabs/s2n-bignum/commit/bac30724f87c03e8851c119fd583d3e429e8027e', 'distinct': True, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/alexw91/aws-lc/commits/76863603a3f3ffa1bdaa6223111a6412e907d6c6'}, {'sha': 'a8e3b92237dd5c190dd3b3bb80d445a2bafcd5f6', 'author': {'email': 'jargh@amazon.com', 'name': 'John Harrison'}, 'message': 'Switch P-256 and P-384 code from assembler macros to C preprocessor

This is a superficial but syntactically messy change to avoid use of
the assembler .macro construct in the P-256 and P-384 functions, for
both ARM and x86 (so now macros are only used in the "fastmul"
functions), replaced by use of the C preprocessor. This is intended to
ease a FIPS build of the code, but does have the side-effect that
preprocessed code can now have multiple instructions per line
separated by semicolons. This is unproblematic for gcc or the GNU
assembler.

Took the chance to make one trivial but semantically meaningful
change, slightly tweaking x86/p384/bignum_tomont_p384.S in line with
earlier changes to the Montgomery multiplication to shorten the code a
bit and keep the identically-named "macros" the same.

'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/lrstewart/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': "### Resolved issues:

Replaces https://github.com/aws/s2n-tls/pull/3170

### Description of changes: 
NIST has [approved](https://csrc.nist.gov/Projects/Post-Quantum-Cryptography/faqs) hybrid key exchange for FIPS mode. This PR therefore enables PQ in FIPS mode.

I only enabled PQ with awslc-fips for now -- openssl-1.0.2-fips does not appear to support the necessary features.

### Testing:
* Unit: existing tests should be sufficient. I audited that none appear to have been gated on fips instead of pq
* Integrationv1: I enabled fips for awslc in both the pq and the client endpoints tests.
* Integrationv2: Currently the v2 tests only build with openssl-1.1.1. I'm not sure how we would communicate the libcrypto library to the tests if they did run with multiple libcryptos, so I didn't add the functionality. When we eventually run the v2 tests on awslc-fips, they will fail because they will not expect pq ciphers to be negotiated.


By submitting this pull request, I confirm that my contribution is made under the terms of the Apache 2.0 license.

I only enabled PQ with awslc-fips for now -- openssl-1.0.2-fips does not appear to support the necessary features.

### Testing:
* Unit: existing tests should be sufficient. I audited that none appear to have been gated on fips instead of pq
* Integrationv1: I enabled fips for awslc in both the pq and the client endpoints tests.
* Integrationv2: Currently the v2 tests only build with openssl-1.1.1. I'm not sure how we would communicate the libcrypto library to the tests if they did run with multiple libcryptos, so I didn't add the functionality. ### Description of changes: 
NIST has [approved](https://csrc.nist.gov/Projects/Post-Quantum-Cryptography/faqs) hybrid key exchange for FIPS mode. This PR therefore enables PQ in FIPS mode.

I only enabled PQ with awslc-fips for now -- openssl-1.0.2-fips does not appear to support the necessary features.

### Testing:
* Unit: existing tests should be sufficient. I audited that none appear to have been gated on fips instead of pq
* Integrationv1: I enabled fips for awslc in both the pq and the client endpoints tests.
* Integrationv2: Currently the v2 tests only build with openssl-1.1.1. I'm not sure how we would communicate the libcrypto library to the tests if they did run with multiple libcryptos, so I didn't add the functionality. When we eventually run the v2 tests on awslc-fips, they will fail because they will not expect pq ciphers to be negotiated.

Request](https://github.com/awslabs/aws-crt-java/pull/323/files#diff-f1aab4617eaab3b72c27aba06813c82260b9c539ca342e58824feaed4e7c4974L74-R79) a change was made to replace the backing native object map when in debug mode from a `ConcurrentHashMap` to a `HashMap` that used the `synchronized` keyword on the class name. 

While this implementation is also correct, it has slower performance than continuing to use `ConcurrentHashMap` when in debug mode. Synchronization will lock the entire HashMap any time any thread is adding or removing any time from the Map, and will cause contention issues if multiple threads are making reads/writes simultaneously. Whereas ConcurrentHashMap only locks a small inner subset of the backing Map during reads/writes, and makes it much less likely that two threads will create contention issues if both are making modifications simultaneously.

For more info on this, see:
 - https://web.archive.org/web/20210122220134/https://www.ibm.com/developerworks/java/library/j-jtp08223/index.html
 - https://stackoverflow.com/questions/1291836/concurrenthashmap-vs-synchronized-hashmap
 - https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/difference-between-concurrenthashmap-and-synchronizedhashmap/
